\begin_layout Standard
Beginning in the late 1990s, Professor David Teece of the University of
 California at Berkeley studied competitive differentiation from an organization
al-behavior perspective.
 He established that organizational competencies can trump resource- and
 positioning-based advantages emphasized by Porter and Christensen.
 Teece called his framework 
\emph on
Dynamic Capabilities
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece1998,Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Organizations possessing this characteristic adaptively reconfigure themselves
 in response to emergent opportunities or threats.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Martin Reeves, leader of Boston Consulting Group's Henderson Research Institute,
 formulated a similar 
\emph on
Adaptivity-Advantage
\emph default
 concept into a consulting framework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Adaptivity Advantage appears influenced by technology-based concepts such
 as 
\emph on
Enterprise Architecture
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ross2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Reeves apparently views technology as an essential enabler for organizational-b
ehavior-based dynamic capabilities Teece describes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bessen2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, Porter first noticed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the information revolution sweeping through our economy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the mid-1980s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Peter Drucker, father of modern business consulting, observed a few years
 later that information and knowledge contribute more to corporate returns
 than traditional real and financial assets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Reeves bridges this concept to his adaptivity-advantage framework by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Competing on the Rate of Learning
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamlett2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes three distinct distinct modes that produce competitive differentiatio
n based on information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion that 
\emph on
information is a strategic asset
\emph default
 remains an emerging theme in business strategy.
 Platform operating models comprise one important manifestation of information-c
entric business models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Evans2016,VanAlstyne2016,Iansiti2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 An information-centric strategic framework might also blend concepts from
 disruptive innovation and dynamic capabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Topic-analysis modeling approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 depicts the fundamental concept underlying topic analysis using Latent
 Dirichlet Allocation (LDA).
 It is aptly named.
 LDA attempts to infer membership in 
\emph on
Latent
\emph default
 topic
\emph on
 
\emph default
classes for each document.
 It belongs to a more-general family of methods called 
\emph on
Latent Variable Models
\emph default
 (
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Loehlin2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\emph on
Dirichlet
\emph default
 refers to a key probability distribution on which the model is based 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "chapter 10"
key "Evans1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
Allocation
\emph default
 pertains to the use of 
\emph on
soft
\emph default
 logic to associate documents with topic classes.
 Rather than trying to definitively link a given document to a distinct
 class, LDA estimates the probability that the document belongs to each
 class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To reiterate, LDA is an 
\emph on
unsupervised
\emph default
-learning approach.
 Its topic-to-document associations do not require a priori, exogenous assignmen
t of documents to topics.
 Such associations are expensive, usually manually produced by subject-matter
 experts (SMEs) for a subset of a corpus.
 Unsupervised-learning methods give us a path to minimize the use of expensive
 SME labor to make topic associations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 represents the LDA's informational structure using a 
\emph on
graph
\emph default
.
 Belonging to the family of 
\emph on
Probabilistic Graphical Models
\emph default
 (PGMs) (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Koller2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), LDA is also a 
\emph on
generative
\emph default
 model.
 It assumes that authors intend to compose documents addressing specific
 topics.
 
\emph on
Topics
\emph default
 generate 
\emph on
Terms
\emph default
, of which 
\emph on
Documents
\emph default
 are comprised.
 Topics are latent variables, here, in that they are not explicitly observable
 in the corpus.
 The LDA model infers each document's association with topics.
\end_layout

