name "LDA Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Documents/GitHub/UncertaintResearch/Biz-StratTopicAnalysis/graphics/200309 Key Analysis Associationssvg.svg.png
	lyxscale 25
	width 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textcolor{Lake}{light-blue-colored 
\backslash
emph{graph edges}} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 — arrows — are labeled with the
\emph on
 conditional-probability estimates
\emph default
 produced by the LDA model.
 Such quantities are typical of PGM approaches.
 Specifically, 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr\left\{ \textrm{Term}\mid\textrm{Topic}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the probability that a given topic produces the corresponding term.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr\left\{ \textrm{Topic}\mid\textrm{Document}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the probability that a given document is associated with a particular
 topic.
 We can alternatively get 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr\left\{ \textrm{Document}\mid\textrm{Topic}\right\} $
\end_inset

 via Bayesian-inversion techniques 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "§9.3.1"
key "Koller2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This latter probability would be of particular use for researchers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 also 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textcolor{TCotta}{shows 
\backslash
emph{Themes} in a distinct color}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from topics and documents.
 Themes are what interest us.
 An LDA model infers topics, which may be distinct from themes.
 The LDA literature (
\emph on
e.g.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Blei2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) makes no mention whatsoever of themes.
 Keeping this in mind is important when interpreting model's results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with many unsupervised-learning methods, we must specify the quantity
 of topics to which the LDA model allocates probabilities.
 This occurs through a combination of analysts' judgment and trial and error.
 We train a large number of LDA models with different topic counts and score
 them statistically.
 We pick the model with the best statistical scores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Extension"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 depicts the concept — not demonstrated presently — for extending our LDA
 topic allocations to themes.
 Candidate approaches remain under consideration.
 Our LDA model gives us document-to-topic associations.
 
\emph on
We seek document-to-theme associations
\emph default
.
 This requires a second stage of probability allocation.
 The desired approach minimizes use of SME touch labor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Concept for extending LDA to associate model-induced topics with researcher-iden
tified themes.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "LDA Extension"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Documents/GitHub/UncertaintResearch/Biz-StratTopicAnalysis/graphics/200410 Topic to Theme.svg.png
	lyxscale 25
	width 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This second stage of allocation might be accomplished through a combination
 of supervised- and unsupervised-learning modeling techniques.
 A second unsupervised-learning stage — accomplished via a simpler technique
 than LDA — might give us clusters in LDA-topic space.
 A combination of topic-space dimensionality and non-lantent cluster analyses
 might also inform our decision regarding the number of LDA clusters to
 fit the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Operationally, a thematic-assignment model might adaptively learn as SMEs
 provide additional documents with known-theme assignments.
 Following a Bayesian-inspired methodology, topic-to-theme probability allocatio
ns are progressively updated as researchers identify new known-theme documents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Preliminary, illustrative results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A small number of 
\emph on
known-theme
\emph default
 documents are used to for a preliminary illustration of LDA topic modeling.
 These are listed in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme docs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Samples were cursorily selected to get at least one example for each of
 the five themes.
 Many of these were referenced above in the 
\emph on
Dominant-themes
\emph default
 subsection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The LDA model was first trained using the 5,000-document, 
\begin_inset Formula $1.25\times10^{6}$
\end_inset

-term corpus described above.
 The known-theme documents in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme docs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 were then applied to the trained model.
 We focus specifically on the resulting document-to-topic probability allocation
s.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demonstration using these documents preliminarily illustrates LDA functional
ity.
 This by no means satisfies the criteria of a formally-designed statistical
 experiment (
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lawson2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 At this instance, we simply seek to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exercise the machinery
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 More-rigorous characterization awaits the sequel.
\end_layout

