\begin_layout Standard
One might naïvely consider assigning a 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Document}_{n}$
\end_inset

 to the category 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\kappa}_{n}=\arg\max_{\kappa}Pr\bigl(\textrm{Topic}_{\kappa}\mid\textrm{Document}_{n}\bigr)\textrm{.}
\]

\end_inset

But, this would not produce high-confidence assignments.
 The highest conditional probability in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme allocations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\kappa,n}Pr\bigl(\textrm{Topic}_{\kappa}\mid\textrm{Document}_{n}\bigr)\approx0.17\textrm{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme allocations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, LDA-inferred topics by themselves do not appear to sharply discriminate
 between themes attributed to the known-theme documents.
 We see considerable overlap, for example, between 
\emph on
Dynamic Capabilities
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Information as an Asset
\emph default
 themes.
 Similarly, the 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr\bigl(\textrm{Topic}_{\kappa}\mid\textrm{Document}_{n}\bigr)$
\end_inset

s for the 
\emph on
Competitive Advantage
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Disruptive Innovation
\emph default
 themes also substantially coincide.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
What do we believe is going on here?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That our model appears not to resolve themes well seems disconcerting at
 first blush.
 Thinking more-deeply, we hypoethesize explanations.
 This is the first step in improving our thematic-discriminant power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
What you say versus what you mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must think carefully about what LDA text-mining is actually doing.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 calls deliberate attention to the distinction between 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textcolor{Night}{
\backslash
textbf{Topics}}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textcolor{Brick}{
\backslash
textbf{Themes}}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 What's the difference? 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Blei2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 distinguishes between 
\emph on
syntax
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
semantics
\emph default
.
 Syntax pertains to the vocabulary and grammar of language.
 Semantics addresses the implicit meaning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Blei2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 makes clear that LDA makes no inferences about documents' semantics: The
 meaning intended by the author.
 
\emph on
Topics
\emph default
 inferred by LDA are derived from the syntax.
 LDA operates on documents' syntax: Vocabulary and, to a lesser extent,
 grammar.
 In fact, LDA's derivation makes use 
\emph on
exchangeability
\emph default
, a prominent result from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "§11.4"
key "deFinetti1970"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Exchangeabilty explicitly proscribes against any assumptions about ordering
 of the terms in documents.
 The resulting groupings may be more informationally-rich than those from
 other machine-learning methods.
 They remain nonetheless syntactic derivatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Themes, in contrast, reside in the realm of 
\emph on
semantics
\emph default
.
 When distinct themes' lexicons overlap significantly, bridging between
 semantics and syntax requires inductive logic, at which statistical algorithms
 tend to struggle 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stove1986,Briggs2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Human cognition's advantage over machine-calculated statistical deduction
 persists for this type of reasoning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Kown-theme interpretation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 presents a qualitative summary of the quantitative results in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme allocations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We use Porter's 
\emph on
Competitive Advantage
\emph default
 framework as a baseline.
 The analysis in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Kown-theme interpretation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 notes that many of the themes use similar vernaculars.
 Recalling that LDA operates largely on syntax — vocabulary and grammar
 — coincidence between themes with overlapping vocabularies is unsurprising.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr\bigl(\textrm{Topic}_{\kappa}\mid\textrm{Document}_{n}\bigr)$
\end_inset

 estimates in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme allocations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Kown-theme interpretation"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/nhamlett/Documents/GitHub/UncertaintResearch/Biz-StratTopicAnalysis/graphics/200408 Thematic-Alignment Summary.svg.png
	lyxscale 25
	width 8.5cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
More to it than that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our cursory demonstration here focuses on five distinct themes.
 The last 40 years of business-strategy discourse has covered many more
 topics than these.
 Our cursory model employed ten latent-topic classes to look for five themes.
 The 5,500-document, 
\begin_inset Formula $1.25\times10^{6}$
\end_inset

-word corpus spans a diverse set of concepts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond that, many documents will span multiple topics.
 This will become particulary pronounced as we move from only titles and
 abstracts to full-text articles.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme allocations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides a preliminary hint of this.
 
\emph on
Text Segmentation
\emph default
 is a method to deal with this 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Memmon2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This involves trying to break documents into topic-distinct segments.
 One thereby obtains topically-distinct sub-documents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Remaining work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preceding sets the stage for subsequent work in preparation for the
 final presentation to the Annual Meeting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Extend the corpus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preceding analysis is based on only titles and abstracts.
 Orthodoxy in the applied-statistics community holds that greater quantities
 of data produce better results.
 (See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wilson2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a contrarian view.) Titles and abstracts provide an easy starting point.
 Most publishers make them generally available.
 They suffice to exercise the end-to-end topic-modeling machinery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Expanding the corpus to full-text articles will be the next step.
 This represents a tradeoff.
 Full-text articles will not be accessible for all journals.
 In terms of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we definitely will end up with more 
\emph on
Terms
\emph default
 for modeling.
 We may have fewer 
\emph on
Documents
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whether to mix in documents, for which only title and abstract are available
 with full-text documents will be weighed.
 Fortunately, the journals for which full-text articles are accessible account
 for a majority of the documents.
 This will provide a corpus whose dimensions roughly coincide with that
 used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Liu2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Expand the use of grammatical information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preceding work is largely vocabulary-based, and only makes minimal use
 of grammatical content.
 Getting LDA-inferred topics that more-closely coincide with themes may
 be enhanced by making more-extensive use of the grammatical structure of
 the corpus.
 More-advanced annotation allows us to pull in more grammatical information
 into the model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Weiss2010,JSLabs"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Additional model optimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Tuning
\emph default
 — looking for the best model parameters — is part of any statistical-modeling
 activity.
 The preceding work tuned the LDA model using a rather textbook, pedestrian
 approach.
 Opportunities remain to improve the amount of information that the LDA
 model extracts from the corpus.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamlett2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates a dimensional analysis of the vocabulary space.
 This could help find the optimum vocabulary size, limited only to the 
\emph on
Terms
\emph default
 that convey the greatest amount of information about the corpus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Extend the LDA model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
LDA-inferred 
\emph on
Topics
\emph default
 may not suffice to discriminate between topics of different themes.
 The results from Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Known-theme allocations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Kown-theme interpretation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 appear to indicate this.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Xie2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 illustrated the combination of LDA with other text-mining methods.
 This in of itself does not appear to give the theme-discriminating power
 we seek.
 Extensions to the LDA model suggested by Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "LDA Extension"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 potentially get us to greater theme-discriminant power.
\end_layout

